<P>FEUDAL TIMES; OR, <HI>THE BANQUET-GALLERY:</HI> A DRAMA, IN TWO ACTS.</P>
<P>FIRST REPRESENTED AT THE THEATRE-ROYAL, DRURY-LANE, ON SATURDAY, JAN. 19TH. 1799.</P>
<P>WRITTEN BY GEORGE COLMAN, THE YOUNGER.</P>
<Q><P>&mdash;SAEPE INTEREUNT ALIIS MEDITANTES NECEM.</P>
<BIBL>PHAEDRUS.</BIBL></Q>
<P><HI>LONDON:</HI> PRINTED BY T. WOODFALL; FOR MESSRS. CADELL AND DAVIES, STRAND.</P>
<P>[PRICE ONE SHILLING AND SIXPENCE.]</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1>
<PB N="iii" REF="2">
<P>HE who hopes to increa&s;e his reputa|tion, (if he have any already) as a Writer, by &s;ketching a mere vehicle for Sing-&s;ong, and Shew,&mdash;is a Block|head. He who indites an elaborate Critici&s;m, on &s;uch a vehicle,&mdash;is a Block|head;&mdash;or, he is wor&s;e:&mdash;a malignant fellow, pretending to mi&s;take a Dra|mati&s;t's Jerkin, for his be&s;t 'Coat, that he may pick a hole in it.</P>
<P>Be it known to you, <HI>Me&s;&s;ieurs!</HI> that this &s;ame &s;cribbling <HI>in a jerkin,</HI>&mdash;but, by the way, it mu&s;t not be ragged,&mdash;is be&s;t &s;uited to &s;ome occa&s;ions; and not at all di&s;re&s;pectful to the Company.&mdash;To have aim'd at writing in <HI>full dre&s;s,</HI> in the pre|&s;ent in&s;tance, would have been a wa&s;te of wardrobe;&mdash;and, as idle, and ex|travagant, as riding on hor&s;e-back, in Hyde Park, in a bag-wig and &s;word.</P>
<P><PB N="iv" REF="3">The &s;ame motives which induced me to con&s;truct the Romance of <HI>Blue-Beard,</HI> and the uncommon favour it has ex|perienced from the Town, tempted me to fabricate <HI>Feudal Times:</HI>&mdash;and my en|deavours to amu&s;e the good Holiday-folks, of London, and to &s;erve the in|tere&s;ts of the Theatre, have again &s;uc|ceeded.</P>
<P>My Coadjutors, in this <HI>Spectacle,</HI> are the &s;ame as in <HI>Blue-Beard;</HI> and I have now, as full a tribute of prai&s;e, and thanks, to render to the Compo&s;er of the Mu&s;ick, to the Machini&s;t, and to the Scene-Painter, as I had to offer when they exerted their talents for me, la&s;t year.</P>
<P>To all the Performers, in the Piece, I make my be&s;t acknowledgments.</P>
<P><PB N="v" REF="4">In the Scene of the Banquet-Gallery, I owe &s;omething to a foreign Dramati&s;t. If any one &s;hould have curio&s;ity, or lei&s;ure enough, to inquire how much, or how little, I am obliged to him, let him peru&s;e <HI>Tarare,</HI> written by <HI>Mon&s;. Beaumarchais.</HI></P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED><HI>GEORGE COLMAN, the Younger.</HI></SIGNED>
<DATELINE><DATE>13th <HI>Feb.</HI> 1799.</DATE><HI>Piccadilly.</HI></DATELINE>
<POSTSCRIPT>
<P>P. S. I had almo&s;t overlook'd the Black-Letter Gentlemen; who may cavil at the term, <HI>Banquet-Gallery.</HI> I could defend it, &s;toutly, under the cir|cum&s;tances in which I have u&s;ed it:&mdash; <HI>mais le jeu ne vaut pas la chandelle.</HI> I leave the di&s;cu&s;&s;ion to Antiquaries, and Nomenclators;&mdash;who&s;e attention (with|out
<PB N="vi" REF="5">
meaning the &s;lighte&s;t offence to a learned, and indefatigable body of men) has often been &s;edulou&s;ly em|ployed upon a &s;ubject of as little im|portance.</P>
</POSTSCRIPT></CLOSER>
</DIV1>
