<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB REF="7">
<HEAD>FEUDAL TIMES; OR <HI>THE BANQUET-GALLERY.</HI></HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE I.</HI> A VILLAGE, in front, on the borders of an ex|ten&s;ive Lake.&mdash;Villagers, male and female, di&s;co|vered, at work. Men mending boats; Women ma|king nets; &amp;c. &amp;c.&mdash;All picture&s;quely grouped. On the Lake is an I&s;land, in which is a &s;tately Ca&s;tle. A rude Rock, ri&s;ing above the water, be|tween the Ca&s;tle, and the &s;hores of the Village. Beyond the Lake, a wild mountainous Scenery.</HEAD>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1>
<HEAD>CHORUS OF VILLAGERS.</HEAD>
<L>BY the &s;ide of the Lake live we;</L>
<L>Sing hey down derry!</L>
<L>And when, in the water, our faces we &s;ee,</L>
<L>We view the reflection of plea&s;ure and glee;</L>
<L>For a Fi&s;herman's life is merry.</L>
<L>Sing hey down derry.</L>
<L><PB REF="8">Well, neighbour, well!</L>
<L>Though here, in poverty, we dwell,</L>
<L>It has been many a Great One's lot,</L>
<L>Since this good World began,</L>
<L>To envy the happine&s;s, &s;ound in the Cot,</L>
<L>Of an humble Fi&s;herman.</L>
<L>By the &s;ide of the Lake, &amp;c.</L>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE><HI>A Flag is di&s;play'd, on the battlements of the Ca&s;tle.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1<HI>&s;t. Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There! There's the flag!&mdash;The old &s;ignal of preparation, from the Ca&s;tle.&mdash;The Ba|ron, I warrant, is going to make war on his an|cient foe, and calls us to duty.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>A Gun is fired, from the Ca&s;tle.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2<HI>d. Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hark!&mdash;Nay, now 'tis certain. Away with our nets, boys! and let fi&s;h live awhile, that fle&s;h may die. We mu&s;t change our oars for battle-axes; and thru&s;t our &s;words, like hooks, into the gills of the enemy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Old Woman.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! I like not the&s;e wars, between the Barons. War, alas! is a keen ravi&s;her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3<HI>d. Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Umph! he mu&s;t be keen, indeed, an he meddle with you, dame.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Old Woman.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Many a youthful flower is mow'd down in the field of &s;laughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2<HI>d. Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>True, my old Daffy-down-dilly, run to &s;eed! But, we are all va&s;&s;als of Baron Fitzal|an: and, as he is ever relieving, or preventing
<PB N="3" REF="9">
the di&s;tre&s;&s;es of his people, 'tis meet we fight lu&s;ti|ly in his cau&s;e. Poor fellows fight with double zeal for a man in command when his humanity goes hand in hand with his power.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3<HI>d. Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Look yonder comes a boat from the Ca&s;tle. We &s;hall hear all, anon.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>A boat puts off from the Ca&s;tle. All the men in the boat are dre&s;&s;'d in the Uniform of Baron Fitzallan. Andrew &s;its at the &s;tern, with a trumpet, and a flag. The boat proceeds from the Ca&s;tle, and at la&s;t reaches the &s;hore of the Village. The boat and men appear &s;mall at fir&s;t, and larger as they ap|proach, to keep up the per&s;pective. Mu&s;ick from the boat, all the way&mdash;at fir&s;t gentle, then increa|&s;ing, gradually, in force, as the di&s;tance is dimini&s;h|ed.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>having landed, and marching in with his men.</HI></STAGE>Long live Baron Fitzallan!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>All.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Huzza!!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Good fellows, and true! all &s;ound to a man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1<HI>&s;t. Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sound? Aye, as roaches, my boy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well &s;aid, my jolly Cock-lob&s;ter of the lake!&mdash;Now, li&s;ten to the voice of mild in|&s;truction.&mdash;<STAGE><HI>blows his trumpet</HI></STAGE> There! that means War.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1<HI>&s;t. Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>We know it, Andrew.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="4" REF="10">
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A true emblem; for it has put me clean out of breath:&mdash;and, War will, &s;ometimes, &s;o take away a man's breath that he can never af|ter recover it.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;All ye Northern men, and Va&s;&s;als of the good Baron Fitzallan! Re|pair, &s;traight, to the Ca&s;tle of the Lake. There to take arms, in the cau&s;e of your Liege-Lord. Maintain his Honour&mdash;for his Honour maintains You. Support the ju&s;t, oppo&s;e the wicked, thump his enemies, a&s;&s;ert his rights, and revenge his wrongs. Huzza! Ble&s;s the Crier!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>4<HI>th. Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>We fight on the old ground, if I mi&s;take not, Andrew? The ancient enmity 'twixt our Lord, here, and the Baron Ruthen|wolf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Partly &s;o.&mdash;'Tis a fre&s;h &s;prout, from the old root.&mdash;'Tis wonderful to &s;ee how un|neighbourly a neighbour can be in this world!&mdash; Truly, our Baron has good cau&s;e of complaint.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>4<HI>th. Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What may the cau&s;e be, Andrew?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A lovely one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3<HI>d. Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How, lovely?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A Woman. No le&s;s than the Lady Claribel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Old Man.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What! the fair daughter of old Sir Philip Portingale?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>E'en &s;he&mdash;who was betroth'd to our Baron's younge&s;t &s;on&mdash;the gallant Edmund Fitz|allan.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="5" REF="11">
<SPEAKER><HI>Old Man.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Heaven ble&s;s him! He is the pride of his hou&s;e, and the joy of all our village. I do think, truly, of all our Baron's goodly &s;ons, young ma&s;ter Edmund is the be&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2<HI>d. Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But how, I prithee, Andrew, is Lady Claribel the cau&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, that viperly Baron&mdash;Ruthen|wolf&mdash;has carried her forcibly away, from her father's;&mdash;ju&s;t as her marriage, with young Ed|mund, was about to be &s;olemnized.&mdash;Thus, Sir Philip has lo&s;t a daughter; the Lady has lo&s;t her lover; Edmund has lo&s;t a wife; the Par&s;on his marriage fee; and you have lo&s;t an ox, roa&s;ted, with his horns on, and three hog &s;heads of old October.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>We'll &s;pill the la&s;t drop of our blood for the hou&s;e of Fitzallan.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Are you all agreed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>All.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>All!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Put your&s;elves in order then.&mdash; March to your boats; paddle away to the Ca&s;tle; &mdash;there take arms;&mdash;then over the mountain, yonder, to attack Ruthenwolf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, neighbours!&mdash;Range your&s;elves! Strike up our old North Country March, that always in&s;pires us for battle; and away!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>The Villagers form them&s;elves in military order:&mdash; Andrew, with his men, at the head of them.&mdash;
<PB N="6" REF="12">
While the following Chorus is &s;inging, they march to the boats in proce&s;&s;ion.&mdash;The Boats proceed round the Rock, and are &s;een dimini&s;hing in per|&s;pective, till &s;ome of the fir&s;t reach the Ca&s;tle-&s;teps, and the men a&s;cend them.&mdash;At the end of the Cho|rus, the Scene clo&s;es.</HI></STAGE>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1>
<HEAD>CHORUS, AND MARCH.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>MARCH, my Companions, March!</L>
<L>Over the mountain we go,</L>
<L>When a Ma&s;ter is kind,</L>
<L>He always will find</L>
<L>A Servant that's faithful, thro' fro&s;t and &s;now&punc;</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>March, my Companions, March!</L>
<L>Stout Engli&s;hmen are we;</L>
<L>He who comforts the poor</L>
<L>May always be &s;ure</L>
<L>To find good &s;upport in his Pea&s;antry,</L>
<L>March, my Companions, March!</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Bleak though the wind &s;hould blow;</L>
<L>Though the mountain were cover'd with &s;now,</L>
<L>Should a loved Ma&s;ter be forlorn,</L>
<L>The Pea&s;ant, then, will wind his horn,</L>
<L>To fight in his cau&s;e, and relieve his woe.</L>
<L>March, my Companions, March!</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="7" REF="13">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE II.</HI> The Skirts of the Village:&mdash;Woody, and Retired.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RACHAEL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I tremble le&s;t my Martin &s;hould keep his word, and come to me, to day. He knows not that the knavery of his Ma&s;ter is di&s;cover'd; and that all our people are up in arms, and going to attack him. Martin is known here, as the chief &s;ervant of Baron Ruthenwolf;&mdash;and &s;hould he be &s;ound lurking about the village, alas! his life would be forfeit.&mdash;Ah, my Martin! I wouldn't have thee come to harm, for the world!</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG&mdash;RACHAEL.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>FIRST beneath a willow's &s;hade,</L>
<L>Heigho! nonino!</L>
<L>Martin, his addre&s;&s;es paid.</L>
<L>Heigho! nonino!</L>
<L>When he whi&s;per'd, &s;ay, &s;incerely,</L>
<L>If you e'er could love me dearly?</L>
<L>All the an&s;wer that I made</L>
<L>Was&mdash;Heigho, nonino!</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Sweet, &s;aid he, were Martin dead,</L>
<L>Heigho! nonino!</L>
<L>One &s;ad tear would Rachael &s;hed?</L>
<L>Heigho! nonino!</L>
<L><PB N="8" REF="14">When my Martin talk'd of dying,</L>
<L>How could I refrain from &s;ighing?</L>
<L>From my heart a murmur fled,</L>
<L>Of&mdash;Heigho! nonino!</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Martin told me, when I figh'd,</L>
<L>Heigho! nonino!</L>
<L><HI>Yes</HI> mu&s;t, always, be implied,</L>
<L>By Heigho, nonino.</L>
<L>Then, &s;ays he, your thoughts di&s;cover,</L>
<L>Will you take me for your lover?&mdash;</L>
<L>Looking down, I blu&s;h'd, and cried&mdash;</L>
<L>Heigho! nonino!</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MARTIN, (<HI>agitated.</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Martin!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Rachael I&mdash;How do'&s;t do, &s;weet?&mdash; I have been &s;o &s;et upon by&mdash;How do'&s;t do?&mdash; I was going to damn all the fi&s;hermen of your village;&mdash;but I forgot that your father amu&s;es him&s;elf with catching flounders, and &s;elling them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Dear! you look pale!&mdash;Has any ac|cident befallen you, on your way hither?&mdash;Our people are all up in arms, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes.&mdash;I know every thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who told you, Martin?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Three gruff-looking fellows, on the border of the lake.&mdash;They told me all:&mdash;and
<PB N="9" REF="15">
then beat the information into my head, with the butt-end of an oar.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy!&mdash;By what means did you e&s;cape?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>By a noble enemy!&mdash;Your Baron's younge&s;t &s;on; the brave Edmund Fitzallan. He came up, by mere accident, as I was about to be butcher'd, and re&s;cued me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What he!&mdash;He whom your ma&s;ter has &s;o much wrong'd!&mdash;He did not know you, &s;ure!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, his words proved that he did. For finding, upon que&s;tion, that I came not as a &s;py, you are without arms, &s;aid he, and at my mercy: An enemy, in &s;uch a ca&s;e, has always a claim up|on a brave man's protection. Get thee back, to Ruthenwolf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven ble&s;s him!&mdash;You are bound to love him, Martin!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Love him! He has &s;aved my life, Ra|chael&mdash;nobly &s;aved it!&mdash;And, may I die like a dog if ever I avoid an opportunity of &s;hewing gratitude to my benefactor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The opportunity may &s;oon come, Mar|tin. You know that Baron Ruthenwolf, whom you have the honour to &s;erve&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Harkye, Rachael&mdash;I have the honour to &s;erve a damn'd &s;coundrel. His head's hot; his
<PB N="10" REF="16">
heart's hard; his face fro&s;ty, and his malice ever|la&s;ting.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy! I wouldn't live in a hou&s;e with &s;uch a mon&s;ter, for the world!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What, not with me in the hou&s;e with you, Rachael?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>&s;miling</HI></STAGE>Nay, that indeed&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What a rare &s;weetner love is! Give a woman the man of her heart, and &s;he'll &s;tomach any thing:&mdash;Ju&s;t as children take phy&s;ick, to get a lump of &s;ugar for &s;wallowing it. Now li&s;ten, Rachael&mdash;I am &s;ent expre&s;sly, by Baron Ruthen|wolf, to bring you with me, to his Ca&s;tle, to at|tend on the Lady Claribel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What, on her, whom he has &s;tolen?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;ame.&mdash;Poor &s;oul! he has made my heart bleed for her. His barbarity&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed!&mdash;Why 'tis &s;aid Ruthenwolf loves her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So he does his wine: and he has treated the Lady as he does his liquor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How's that, Martin?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Lock'd her up, in a dark, cool place, underground.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy on me! Is &s;he there, &s;till?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No.&mdash;I am his confidant, you know, as well as his butler: and, la&s;t night, as I drew a bottle of canary, for him from the cellar, when
<PB N="11" REF="17">
he grew warm with it, I per&s;uaded him to let me draw out the dam&s;el from the dungeon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, my Martin! You have a kindly &s;oul!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What, for trying to relieve the &s;orrows of a woman? 'Tis an unkindly &s;oul, indeed, Rachael, that will not &s;trive to &s;uccour a female, whenever &s;he needs a&s;&s;i&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why that may be&mdash;but if all men were like you&mdash;but don't be too tender-hearted to all the women, neither.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There!&mdash;Now you are jealous! Good actions are &s;o rare, now a days, that a plain fellow is always &s;u&s;pected in his motives for doing them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, well, for all that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw!&mdash;non&s;en&s;e!&mdash;A man's kindne&s;s to women, in general, &s;hould rather obtain him credit, when he profe&s;&s;es tenderne&s;s to one, in particular.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, it may be &s;o&mdash;but &s;till&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Pooh!&mdash;prithee&mdash;as if, were I &s;o in|clined&mdash;that a lady, like lady Claribel, would look down on &s;uch a lout as I.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>As you!&mdash;The &s;weete&s;t lady, in the land, might jump at you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Might &s;he!&mdash;You are the &s;weete&s;t to me in the land; &s;o jump at me, and ki&s;s me.<STAGE><HI>&s;he
<PB N="12" REF="18">
jumps on his neck, and ki&s;&s;es him.</HI></STAGE> Well, I am a pretty fellow, that's the tenth on't!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That you are, Martin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And to prove I am true&mdash;ob&s;erve. The lady Claribel is &s;tolen by Ruthenwolf;&mdash;&s;he has a lover in Edmund Fitzallan;&mdash;he has &s;aved my life;&mdash;and, if they come not together, blame my indu&s;try.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But, how to contrive this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Thus&mdash;and you, perhaps, may help me in the contrivance.&mdash;Lord Ruthenwolf has lifted his pri&s;oner from darkne&s;s to light; from the dungeon of horror, to the chamber of fea&s;t|ing.&mdash;He thinks, now, this will be&s;t help forward his &s;uit with her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come with me to my ma&s;ter's.&mdash;We will arrange matters with your father, here, as we pa&s;s.&mdash;and, I will, from his hou&s;e, write a letter to my pre&s;erver, to repair &s;ecretly to Ru|thenwolf Ca&s;tle, as I &s;hall direct him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But if this &s;hould fail, Martin&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw!&mdash;It &s;hall go hard if, with our a&s;&s;i&s;tance, he do not &s;oon re&s;cue his love.&mdash; Away!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I would follow you, Martin, all over the word:&mdash;and now I have a double cau&s;e to
<PB N="13" REF="19">
follow you.&mdash;We mu&s;t be cautious, though, for your &s;ake, in pa&s;&s;ing the village.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>True:&mdash;I may, chance to lo&s;e the little brains I have, el&s;e.&mdash;When we reach the Ca&s;tle, and have &s;aved the&s;e lovers, we will then be married, &s;weet!&mdash;There will be a jovial day!&mdash; We'll have &s;uch a holiday, and merry making!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, that we will!</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1>
<STAGE>DUETT.&mdash;MARTIN AND RACHAEL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>RACHAEL.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>ALL &s;hall leave their labouring;</L>
<L>We'll call each hone&s;t neighbour in;</L>
<L>Heigh! for pipe and taboring,</L>
<L>When I and Martin wed.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARTIN.</SPEAKER>
<L>Never &s;hall our holiday</L>
<L>Be called a melancholy day;</L>
<L>It &s;hall be a jolly $ay</L>
<L>When I and Rachael bed.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BOTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fal de ral de ral, &amp;c.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RACHAEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>Then Martin. &s;weet Martin, &s;ince you have a mind to me,</L>
<L>Pray promi&s;e, when married, always to be kind to me.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="14" REF="20">
<SPEAKER>MARTIN.</SPEAKER>
<L>All that I have, Rachael&mdash;I have little riches though&mdash;</L>
<L>All &s;hall be yours, Rachael&mdash;I mu&s;t wear the breeches though.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BOTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fal de ral de ral, &amp;c.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>RACHAEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>Yet, they &s;ay, love's a doubt;</L>
<L>Marriage often wears it out:&mdash;</L>
<L>Ere a year comes about,</L>
<L>Lo&s;t is love and joy.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARTIN.</SPEAKER>
<L>Ere a year pa&s;&s;es by,</L>
<L>Sure our love will multiply;</L>
<L>Mother you, Father I,</L>
<L>Of a chopping boy!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BOTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fal de ral de ral, &amp;c.</P>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE III.</HI> A Spacious Court, in Fitzallan Ca&s;tle.&mdash;The Villagers drawn up, in Uniforms.&mdash;Andrew reviewing them.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis downright drudgery to drill the&s;e water-varlets for land &s;ervice. They have been
<PB N="15" REF="21">
&s;o u&s;ed to look down in the Lake, for fi&s;h, that there is no making them hold up their heads. What is thy name, friend?<STAGE><HI>to one of the men.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Simon Smallfry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The knave is as unwieldy as a whale; and handles his pike as if 'twere the pole of a punt.&mdash;You are wondrous aukward, friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Vil.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yees&mdash;but I can hit hard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do not doubt it:&mdash;thou ha&s;t a fi&s;t as broad as a frying-pan.&mdash;Be&s;ides, when the times call on an Engli&s;hman for his &s;ervice, put but weapons in his hands, and, though unbred to arms, I'll warrant he'll fight as &s;taunch as a bull|dog.</P>
<STAGE><HI>A Flouri&s;h without.</HI></STAGE>
<P>Hark! The Baron, with his &s;ons, is advancing.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Baron Fitzallan, Henry, Orlando, and Ed|mund: preceded by a Military Band.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>All.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Huzza!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I thank you, friends! This cheers me. The&s;e are the clamours of affection. They &s;alute the ear like ru&s;tick mu&s;ick, mellowing as it floats, o'er the &s;mooth &s;urface of the waters, in a &s;weet &s;ummer's 'night; and &s;oothe the li&s;tener's &s;pirit. &mdash;Are they in&s;tructed in the cau&s;e of our expedi|dition?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="16" REF="22">
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They are, my lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How feel they in it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Andrew.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Like fellows, my lord, with low pockets, who are hone&s;t, and pay their debts by in&s;tal|ment. We owe &s;o much to your goodne&s;s, my lord, that we are rejoiced in this opportunity of di&s;charging a little of our obligations upon ac|count.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Wealth and Power! &s;tretch on your down, and &s;end your emi&s;&s;aries forth, to bring you plea&s;ures which pamper every &s;en&s;e!&mdash;can ye, can ye procure to your&s;elves a nobler luxury than the cheap purcha&s;e of a poor man's gratitude!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Hen.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Say, my father&mdash;&s;hall we begin our march? &mdash;I long to puni&s;h this villain Ruthenwolf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Orl.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And I.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What &s;ay you, Edmund?&mdash;Mo&s;t wrong'd, and yet mo&s;t &s;ilent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My wrongs mu&s;t &s;peak in action. In|&s;ult to you, my lord, to Claribel, to me;&mdash;the&s;e are threefold injuries. Place him before me, he &s;hall meet threefold puni&s;hment.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter a</HI> SERVANT <HI>to</HI> EDMUND.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Serv.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>This letter Sir:&mdash;brought by an old pea&s;ant, from the village:&mdash;who beg'd hard it might be in&s;tantly deliver'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="17" REF="23">
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>in&s;pecting the letter</HI></STAGE>Nay, this concerns us all. I pray you read, my lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>taking the letter, and reading.</HI></STAGE>"Strata|gem may &s;ometimes pro&s;per, where force may fail. Could you contrive, a little after mid|night, to pa&s;s the Porter's Lodge of your enemy, you might then proceed, unob&s;erved, in dark|ne&s;s, to the inner court:&mdash;in which court, &s;hould you perceive lights, from the large win|dow of the Banquet-Gallery, be a&s;&s;ured they are placed there as a token, that you may enter that window with &s;afety.&mdash;The mouldering buttre&s;s, beneath it, mu&s;t &s;erve you for a ladder.&mdash;Enter the window as the Ca&s;tle clock tolls One.&mdash;You will then be conducted to the lady Claribel, by him who this morning owes his life to you."</P>
<P>"MARTIN."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The Va&s;&s;al of Ruthenwolf&mdash;whom I met e'en now, in the village, unarm'd, uncon&s;cious of our prepaations, and re&s;cued from our peo|ple.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Hen.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Re&s;cued him, Edmund!&mdash;The &s;lave of our enemy;&mdash;that villain, Ruthenwolf!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To be a &s;lave, Henry, and &s;lave to a villain, too, is misfortune enough.&mdash;Poor wretch, I pitied him! Compa&s;&s;ion, brother, urges me to afford &s;uccour to a defencele&s;s man, in my
<PB N="18" REF="24">
power, who&s;e hard lot has made it his <HI>duty</HI> to &s;erve an oppre&s;&s;or, whom I mu&s;t puni&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My noble boy!&mdash;Yes, my &s;ons! The &s;laughter of war is man's nece&s;&s;ity; but mercy is his nature. Could the rough &s;oldier, in the trench, find lei&s;ure there to look inward on him|&s;elf, and trace the fine-wrought contexture of his heart, he would mark that He who gave it pul&s;ation has clo&s;ely intertwined the fibres of humanity with courage.&mdash;Edmund, you &s;hall venture on this enterpri&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Orl.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>May there not be treachery in't? This, may be &s;ome lure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Scarcely &s;o. It &s;eems the working of an hone&s;t creature's &s;oul, grateful to his pre&s;er|ver. 'Tis worth the trial:&mdash;And, &s;hould it fail, our troops &s;hall be beneath the Tower, to give you &s;peedy &s;uccour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Be it &s;o order'd, then.&mdash;Yet, let us march forth together. With your good leave, my Lord, we may now proceed to the murky wood, within a league of our enemy. There, 'till near midnight, we may lye in ambu&s;h.&mdash;I will then quit our band, to try my fortune; and you, my Lord, &s;ome little interval given, may, with all your troops, in &s;ilence follow me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Agreed.&mdash;Mu&s;ter our Hou&s;ehold.&mdash;And,
<PB N="19" REF="25">
as they march in our review, produce the Colours, as is our cu&s;tom.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Fitzallan's Sons go to a door in the Ca&s;tle, which is in one wing of the Court, and bring forth the Colours.&mdash;At the &s;ame time, by a &s;ignal given, the Men march in, through the gateway; all arm'd&mdash; they arrange them&s;elves, according to their different ranks, and &s;tations.&mdash;Fitzallan and his Sons heading them, in different divi&s;ions.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Edmund, cheer our &s;oldiers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Friends!&mdash;Prepare.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG AND CHORUS.</HEAD>
<STAGE>EDMUND, SOLDIERS, <HI>and</HI> VASSALS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>EDMUND.</SPEAKER>
<L>TELL me, my gallant Soldiers, tell me true;&mdash;</L>
<L>Hands to your hearts!&mdash;your hearts with valour &s;tored&mdash;</L>
<L>Tell me what Manhood prompts you all to do,</L>
<L>Whene'er a foe in&s;ults your true Liege-Lord.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SOLDIERS.</SPEAKER>
<L>March away,</L>
<L>Without delay!</L>
<L>We'll an&s;wer with the &s;word!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>EDMUND.</SPEAKER>
<L>Or &s;ay, my friends, &s;hould you, like me, be moved;</L>
<L>Or, could you mercy to a fiend afford,</L>
<L>Who rob'd you of the virtuous Maid you loved,</L>
<L>And tore her from an aged Father's board?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="20" REF="26">
<SPEAKER>SOLDIERS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ma.ch away! &amp;c.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>EDMUND.</SPEAKER>
<L>March, then, my gallant &s;oldiers! March, and fight!</L>
<L>Puni&s;h the traitor, ruthle&s;s, and abhor'd.&mdash;</L>
<L>Let Valour's arm be rai&s;ed in Virtue's right,</L>
<L>And follow, to the field, your true Liege-Lord.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SOLDIERS.</SPEAKER>
<L>March away,</L>
<L>Without delay,</L>
<L>We follow with the &s;word.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt, marching.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE IV.</HI> An Apartment in Ruthenwolf Ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CLARIBEL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cla.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Will no friend come!&mdash;my father&mdash;nay, he is drooping on a &s;ick bed. Oh, Edmund! ha&s;t <HI>thou</HI> for&s;aken me!&mdash;Let me be patient&mdash;he is, now, perhaps, planning my relea&s;e.&mdash;Yet to be tortured with the odious love of Ruthen|wolf!&mdash;Alas! there was more hone&s;t tyranny in the Dungeon, whence, ye&s;terday, he drew
<PB N="21" REF="27">
me, than in this gaudy pri&s;on!&mdash;The&s;e glitter|ing chambers mock my &s;orrows.&mdash;Would I were free!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<STAGE>SONG.&mdash;CLARIBEL.</STAGE>
<LG>
<L>OH, the Maid of the Wold, how &s;he traver&s;ed the Land,</L>
<L>To court the rude touches of Winter's chill hand!</L>
<L>The Wind on her bo&s;om of lillies blew bleak,</L>
<L>And the Snow fell, in flakes, on the ro&s;e of her cheek.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Drear, drear was the pro&s;pect; all clouded the Sky;</L>
<L>But the Sun&s;hine of Liberty beam'd in her eye:&mdash;</L>
<L>She cried, while the wet from her ringlets &s;he pre&s;t&mdash;</L>
<L>"I am free as the bla&s;t that blows over my brea&s;t!"</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Sweet Maid of the Wold! as un&s;helter'd you &s;tray,</L>
<L>In that bli&s;s of the Poor&mdash;all the World for your way!&mdash;</L>
<L>If <HI>one</HI> pen&s;ive moment &s;hould flit o'er your mind,</L>
<L>Drop a tear for a Captive, in Splendour confin'd.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RUTHENWOLF.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Claribel&mdash;You know my pur|po&s;e:&mdash;Love.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Clar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Know mine too, Ruthenwolf:&mdash;Rather than yield to it, &mdash;Death.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Troth, Lady, Death has a &s;welling &s;ound, &mdash;when 'tis well thunder'd from the mouth of haughty beauty.&mdash;'Tis a word written&mdash;'mong&s;t other harmle&s;s threats&mdash;in her Di&s;dain's vocabu|lary.&mdash;Yet, place a Woman 'twixt Death and Love, 'tis odds, whene'er the gri&s;ly Monarch,
<PB N="22" REF="28">
in all his terror, &s;cowls upon her, that &s;he will fly for &s;afety to the dimpled God, who &s;preads his wings to &s;helter her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Clar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Lord Ruthenwolf&mdash;The God of Love, whom pure hearts wor&s;hip, received his honied &s;hafts from Honour, and Virtue plumed his pinions. Your Deity&mdash;your Daemon, rather&mdash; is wing'd like Lucifer. Guilt gave the word, and Loath&s;omene&s;s bedeck'd him:&mdash;while Bru|tality &s;tood by, and laugh'd, to think how many of his votaries would violate the innocent. Com|pared to this, Death &s;miles a Cherub.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Since you are thus &s;kill'd in painting Love, fair Lady, it &s;hould &s;eem that you have felt the pa&s;&s;ion he in&s;pires.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Clar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I glory in that pa&s;&s;ion!&mdash;You knew I gloried in it;&mdash;and that knowledge gave &s;purs to your malignity:&mdash;before not &s;luggi&s;h.&mdash;Edmund Fitzallan, &s;ir, ere long, will give it's &s;peed the due reward it merits.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Damnation!&mdash;That name within the&s;e walls!<STAGE><HI>He half draws his &s;word, as intending to &s;tab Claribel&mdash;&s;he throws open her arms, as courting the wound. Ruthenwolf, trembling with contending passions, returns his &s;word to the &s;cabbard.</HI></STAGE> Lady I&mdash;had any tongue but your's thus utter'd, this &s;teel had taught it &s;i|lence.
<PB N="23" REF="29">
Why, why, Madam, will you name my bitter enemy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Clar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Your enemy!&mdash;Oh, true&mdash;His noble heart holds villainy in dete&s;tation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now by my &s;oul! Well, well, I will be calm, Lady. A lover mu&s;t bear all.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MARTIN.</STAGE>
<P>Now, fellow! whence come you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>From performing my commi&s;&s;ion, my Lord. I have been &s;eeking, as you order'd, one to attend on Lady Claribel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well&mdash;the fruit, &s;ir, of your &s;earch?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>RACHAEL <HI>Enters.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Very &s;weet fruit, my Lord.&mdash;From the ripe clu&s;ters of Females, which grow in the neighbourhood, I have pluck'd this blooming gentlewoman.<STAGE><HI>pre&s;enting her</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Can&s;t thou attend a Lady?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I will do my endeavours, &s;o plea&s;e you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Lady Claribel&mdash;Take her to your notice. If &s;oothing, as 'tis &s;aid, can win a Lady's &s;mile, I will e'en &s;leek my brow to the &s;oother's fa&s;hion. What ho, there! Have they prepared the dance?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="24" REF="30"><HI>Enter</HI> SERVANT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ser.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, my Lord. All wait you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>This for our morning revelry. At night the &s;ilver moon, pale in her envy, &s;hall look down upon our ro&s;y orgies. This night, to break a cu&s;tom, we will &s;it late, in fea&s;t.&mdash;We &s;up in the Banquer&mdash;Gallery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The&mdash;the Banquet-Gallery, my Lord! The very place in which I have appointed young Fitzallan!<STAGE><HI>a&s;ide</HI></STAGE> To&mdash;to&mdash;to night, my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, to night.&mdash;How now what ails thee?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>N&mdash;no&mdash;nothing, my Lord.&mdash;Only 'tis &s;o long &s;ince that Banquet-Gallery has been open'd, that the very thoughts of going into it makes me&mdash;hem&mdash;makes me tremble, my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ne'er fear, knave.&mdash;It &s;hall blaze with light:&mdash;And, toward the hour of One, good cheer and mirth &s;hall warm us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>a&s;ide</HI></STAGE>One!&mdash;The very hour on which he is to enter the window!&mdash;And the lights I meant to place there, as a beacon of &s;afety, will prove a decoy for his de&s;truction!&mdash;No appri&s;ing him&mdash; What can I do?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Gay Mu&s;ick, from the interior apartment.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hark!&mdash;The dance invites us. Come Lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="25" REF="31">
<SPEAKER><HI>Clar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>E'en as you plea&s;e. All is alike indiffe|rent to me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay come.&mdash;Follow me, Slave!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Ruthenwolf leads Claribel through the folding doors; Martin and Rachael following, making &s;igns to each other. As &s;oon as they have enter'd the fold|ing doors, the Scene, in&s;tantly, withdraws&mdash;and di&s;covers a magnificent apartment. Va&s;&s;als attend|ing, and Dancers in groupes. Ruthenwolf &s;eats Claribel on a &s;ofa, and &s;its be&s;ide her.</HI></STAGE>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1>
<HEAD>GRAND CHORUS, AND DANCE.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>WHEN old Timotheus touch'd his lyre, to move</L>
<L>Philip's warlike &s;on to love,</L>
<L>The Min&s;trels &s;train</L>
<L>In&s;pired his heart with plea&s;ing pain;</L>
<L>And as the hero &s;unk, with love oppre&s;t,</L>
<L>His willing Thais caught him to her brea&s;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Breathe then a melodious mea&s;ure,</L>
<L>'Till Mu&s;ick melts the &s;oul to plea&s;ure:</L>
<L>And while it lightly floats along the air,</L>
<L>Now, when a warrior feels its power,</L>
<L>May it touch, in happy hour,</L>
<L>The bo&s;om of his fair.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FIRST ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB REF="32">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE I.</HI> The Porter's Hall, in Ruthenwolf Ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE>NICHOLAS, <HI>at a table, drinking</HI>; SUSAN <HI>&s;eated near him. A violent Storm is heard, and the lightning is &s;een fla&s;hing through the window.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>NICHOLAS.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>HERE's weather!&mdash;It blows, and rains, and thunders, and lightens!&mdash;I don't remember a more di&s;mal night, &s;ince I have been Porter in Ruthenwolf Ca&s;tle.&mdash;Well, I am content.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You are always content with good wine before you, father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Su&s;an, your Father's getting in years. Wine comforts the aged. 'Tis a &s;ort of under|wai&s;tcoat
<PB N="27" REF="33">
to a man's in&s;ide;&mdash;and the older he grows the more of this kind of flannel he wants. <STAGE><HI>drinks</HI></STAGE> Next year, I mu&s;t double my cloathing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, Father, you are not &s;o old, nei|ther. You are but forty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But I have been twenty years Porter here: and the labour of office &s;aps the con&s;titu|tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis no &s;uch great labour, father. You have little more than to open and &s;hut the gate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis Porter's work, for all that, Su&s;an. My father,&mdash;your grandfather,&mdash;who held the keys, here, before me, fell under it. Heaven re&s;t him! Death knock'd at his door, and would come in.&mdash;He went off ju&s;t as I was going to give him a gla&s;s of mull'd brandy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They &s;ay, in the neighbourhood, that he kill'd him&s;elf with &s;heer drink.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Scandal. A cen&s;orious world! I &s;houldn't wonder if they &s;aid the &s;ame of me, when I am gone.<STAGE><HI>drinks.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, but my Grandfather&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall never forget his la&s;t advice. "Nicholas," &s;ays he&mdash;I &s;tood by him with the gla&s;s in my hand;&mdash;he couldn't fill it, &s;o I did.&mdash; "Nicholas," &s;ays he, "you are to inherit the keys: Remember, Sobriety and Vigilance!&mdash; That's the Porter's motto."&mdash;and he died.
<PB N="28" REF="34">
Poor &s;oul! he couldn't drink the brandy then:&mdash; &s;o I did.&mdash;I &s;wallow'd it to comfort me; for all the world as I take this gla&s;s of canary.<STAGE><HI>drinks.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h, Father, you would drink no more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! Non&s;en&s;e! Do you think I am always fuddled, like the fat Friar of Nottingham?</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.&mdash;NICHOLAS.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>A jolly fat Friar loved liquor, good &s;tore,</L>
<L>And he had drank &s;toutly at &s;upper;</L>
<L>He mounted his hor&s;e, in the night, at the door,</L>
<L>And &s;at with his face to the crupper.</L>
<L>Some rogue, quoth the Friar, quite dead to remor&s;e,</L>
<L>Some thief, whom a halter will throttle,</L>
<L>Some &s;coundrel, has cut off the head of my hor&s;e,</L>
<L>While I was engaged at the bottle.</L>
<L>Which went gluggity, gluggity, glug, glug, glug&punc;</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>The tail of the &s;teed pointed South, on the dale,</L>
<L>'Twas the Friars road home, &s;trait and level,</L>
<L>But, when &s;pur'd, a hor&s;e follows his no&s;e, not his tail,</L>
<L>So he &s;camper'd due North, like a devil.</L>
<L>This new mode of docking, the Friar, then, &s;aid,</L>
<L>I perceive doesn't make a hor&s;e trot ill;</L>
<L>And 'tis cheap; for he never can eat off his head,</L>
<L>While I am engaged at the bottle:</L>
<L>Which goes gluggity, gluggity, glug, glug, glug.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>The &s;teed made a &s;top; in a pond he had got;</L>
<L>He was rather for drinking than grazing;</L>
<L><PB N="29" REF="35">Quoth the Friar, 'tis &s;trange headle&s;s hor&s;es &s;hould trot;</L>
<L>But to drink with their tails is amazing!</L>
<L>Turning round, to &s;ee whence this Phoenomenon ro&s;e,</L>
<L>In the pond fell this &s;on of a pottle;</L>
<L>Quoth he, the head's found, for I'm under his no&s;e;</L>
<L>I wi&s;h I were over a bottle.</L>
<L>Which goes gluggity, gluggity, glug, glug, glug.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE><HI>The Storm continues.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy on us! What a &s;torm! The rain will beat in the ca&s;ement.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Let me &s;ee that all's tight&mdash;and do you trim up the lamp, Su&s;an.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>While they are employ'd in looking at the window, and trimming the lamp,</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RACHAEL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis near the hour that young Fitzallan &s;hould come. If I could, now, as Martin has told me, contrive to warn him of the danger of coming to the Banquet-Gallery, I&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>Nicholas comes from the Window.</HI></STAGE>
<P>Your &s;ervant, Mr. Nicholas!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, dear! This is Mi&s;tre&s;s Rachael; the new little Gentlewoman they have hired, to wait on the new great Gentlewoman.&mdash;Now&punc; by St. Peter, you are welcome to the Porter's, Hall of Ruthenwolf Ca&s;tle!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="30" REF="36">
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I thank you, good Mr. Nicholas!&mdash;I was willing to pay you a vi&s;it, as we are, now, fellow &s;ervants. The Baron, you know, has en|gaged me, to attend the Lady Claribel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I don't wonder at it, at all;&mdash;for he chu&s;es all his dome&s;ticks good looking. He told me &s;o him&s;elf, when he took me for his Porter. And, this is my good-looking daughter.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>pre&s;enting her.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>La! father, how fooli&s;h!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;ad rainy night, Mr. Nicholas.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sad, indeed!&mdash;We &s;hall all be under water. Take a drop of this, to keep out the cold.<STAGE><HI>offering wine.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I never do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's very odd!&mdash;I always do.&mdash;Here's a bumper to our better acquaintance.<STAGE><HI>drinks.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hark!&mdash;Methought I heard him&mdash;No. <STAGE><HI>a&s;ide.</HI></STAGE> Ah, Mr. Nicholas! in &s;uch nights as the&s;e, I cannot help &s;ighing for the poor travel|ler.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So do I, I'm &s;ure!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Wandering over the wild heath;&mdash;ex|po&s;ed to the Storm;&mdash;no tree to &s;helter him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No kind &s;oul to direct him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No Publick Hou&s;e to be &s;een!<STAGE><HI>drinking.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE>EDMUND FITZALLAN <HI>&s;ings, without.</HI></STAGE>
<Q>"Shelter a way-worn Traveller!"</Q>
<SP>
<PB N="31" REF="37">
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis he! <STAGE><HI>a&s;ide.</HI></STAGE> Hark!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Didn't I hear a voice?&mdash;Li&s;ten.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1>
<HEAD>QUARTETTO.</HEAD>
<STAGE>NICHOLAS, RACHAEL, SUSAN, <HI>and</HI> EDMUND.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>EDMUND.</SPEAKER>
<L>Shelter a way-worn Traveller!</L>
<L>Hard beats the rain; the lightnings play;</L>
<L>Bewilder'd, here, alas! I &s;tray.</L>
<L>Shelter a way-worn Traveller!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NICHOLAS, RACHAEL, SUSAN.</SPEAKER>
<L>Hark! who is that &s;o faintly calls.</L>
<L>Beneath the Ca&s;tle's gloomy walls?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>EDMUND.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Wretched, way-worn Traveller!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NICHOLAS, RACHAEL, SUSAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! a way-worn Traveller!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>EDMUND.</SPEAKER>
<L>O, Shelter! for my Life's at &s;take;</L>
<L>Unbar your Door, for pity's &s;ake!</L>
<L>Within your friendly Turrets take</L>
<L>A wretched, way-worn Traveller!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NICHOLAS, RACHAEL, SUSAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! a way-worn Traveller!</P>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<PB N="32" REF="38">
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Some poor wretch, who has lo&s;t his way!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Dying, perhaps, for want of a&s;&s;i&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Wont you let him in, Mr. Nicholas?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, do, father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>reflecting.</HI></STAGE>Now, am I puzzled:&mdash; and when a man's puzzled, a woman always puzzles him more. Here are two to perplex me. Su&s;an, get you up &s;tairs to your chamber.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Su&s;an.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No words.&mdash;Away! <STAGE><HI>Su&s;an goes out.</HI></STAGE> So; there's one difficulty over.&mdash;Good night, mi&s;tre&s;s Rachael!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Will not you let the Traveller in, then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I want no &s;pies to inform again&s;t me,&mdash; &s;o that's a &s;ecret.&mdash;Will you give me a ki&s;s, to know it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rachael.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>he&s;itating</HI></STAGE>Why, if it were not for my Mart&mdash;I&mdash;Well, I&mdash;I will give you a ki&s;s, to know it.<STAGE><HI>he ki&s;&s;es her.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Mi&s;tre&s;s Rachael, mark this:&mdash; When a pretty woman, like you, thinks a ki&s;s bribe enough for telling a &s;ecret, damn me if I tru&s;t her with mine:&mdash;for &s;he'll meet with a bribe every day.&mdash;Good night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;t I go? <STAGE><HI>he waves his hand.</HI></STAGE> I can|not inform him of his danger, and&mdash;Heaven pre&s;erve him! <STAGE><HI>a&s;ic.</HI></STAGE><STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, I have got the ground to my&s;elf. If Lord Ruthenwolf knows I let a &s;tranger in,
<PB N="33" REF="39">
he'll turn me out. Obedience is a duty I owe to the Baron&mdash;that's a &s;trong rea&s;on again&s;t the gen|tleman on the other &s;ide of the door. <STAGE><HI>Edmund knocks.</HI></STAGE>&mdash;But Pity is a duty I owe to all the un|fortunate, in their time of trouble&mdash;that's a much &s;tronger rea&s;on for the gentleman on the out&s;ide of the door;&mdash;So, in he comes.&mdash;<STAGE><HI>going to the door.</HI></STAGE> I never found out, before, how many poor devils have as great a right to my &s;ervices as my ma&s;ter. <STAGE><HI>he unbars the door, and admits</HI> EDMUND FITZALLAN, <HI>who is muffled up in a Traveller's Cloak.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I thank you, friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>By our lady, you are what I call &s;ou&s;ed! Pour &s;ome of this down your throat.&mdash;<STAGE><HI>Gives him wine.</HI></STAGE>&mdash;It chills me to look at you. It makes me &s;tand in need of a gla&s;s, my&s;elf.&mdash; <STAGE><HI>Drinks.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The knave has drank freely, and &s;eems ripe for my purpo&s;e.&mdash;<STAGE><HI>A&s;ide.</HI></STAGE>&mdash;This is rare li|quor, friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's a pity, for I like plenty of it. Who are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A traveller.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What made you travel here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis a long &s;tory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="34" REF="40">
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Tel! it me.&mdash;I like long &s;tories; they put me &s;o comfortably to &s;leep.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's e'en as I could wi&s;h.&mdash;<STAGE><HI>A&s;ide.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, &s;it down; whet your whi&s;tle, and begin.&mdash;<STAGE><HI>They &s;it and drink.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My father was once affluent; blazed in &s;plendour; each day his hall rang with fe&s;tivity&mdash; for he opened wide the door to many a bidden gue&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So did my father&mdash;he was the Porter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But Fortune varied:&mdash;his e&s;tates dwindled&mdash;his friends faded&mdash;my father died.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And, then, you &s;wallow'd the mull'd brandy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>His &s;en&s;es totter.&mdash;<STAGE><HI>A&s;ide.</HI></STAGE>&mdash;On my fa|ther's death, ruin hung o'er his hou&s;e; 'twas for me to oppo&s;e the &s;torm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>Half a&s;leep.</HI></STAGE>'Thas been a &s;ad &s;torm. Another gla&s;s</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Edmund fills it, Nicholas drinks.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I left my native home&mdash;two days had journey'd&mdash;'till now, travelling o'er the moor&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>Holding out his gla&s;s, and muttering.</HI></STAGE>&mdash; More? More!&mdash;Ah!&mdash;a little more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Evening lowered&mdash;the clouds grew thick. No guide&mdash;the pea&s;ants in their beds&mdash;
<PB N="35" REF="41">
All in the arms of &s;leep.&mdash;<STAGE><HI>Nicholas &s;nores, Ed|mund ri&s;es cautiou&s;ly.</HI></STAGE>&mdash;As thou art now, poor knave! This cloak will but encumber me, as I explore the windings of the Ca&s;tle.&mdash;Then dark|ne&s;s be my &s;hrowd.&mdash;<STAGE><HI>Throws off his cloak.</HI></STAGE>&mdash;And, &s;hould my pre&s;ence create &s;ome havock here, thou, &s;imple &s;oul, &s;halt fare the better for thy courte&s;y to me:&mdash;for the &s;weet godde&s;s, Cha|rity, bad thee unbar the door to me, in the tempe&s;t;&mdash;and Gratitude, her fir&s;t-born daugh|ter, would, from her glowing forehead, dart a frown upon me, could I forget thee.<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Nicholas remains fa&s;t a&s;leep, and the Scene clo&s;es.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE II.</HI> A Colonade in Ruthenwolf Ca&s;tle, leading to the Inner Court.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> EDMUND FITZALLAN.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The clouds have &s;pent their fury; and the dying thunder rolls, &s;ullenly, away, upon the di&s;tant hills. This, I conjecture, will lead me to the inner court; whence I mu&s;t watch the &s;ig|nal, which Martin promi&s;ed.&mdash;The friendly lights
<PB N="36" REF="42">
from the window mu&s;t be my guide.&mdash;It lacks &s;omewhat yet of the time appointed. I will linger here awhile.&mdash;Should any pa&s;s, the&s;e pil|lars will afford concealment.&mdash;Oh, Claribel! how tedious are the hours of doubt and expectation!</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<STAGE>SONG.&mdash;EDMUND.</STAGE>
<LG>
<L>GRANT me her for whom I &s;igh,</L>
<L>In Love's &s;eque&s;ter'd bowers,</L>
<L>Full &s;wiftly would the minutes fly,</L>
<L>Full &s;moothly glide the hours.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>But tear the dear-loved maid away,</L>
<L>Then anxious thoughts the &s;oul engage;</L>
<L>While every minute &s;eems a day,</L>
<L>And every hour&mdash;an age!</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Give me all thou can'&s;t be&s;tow.</L>
<L>Young God of fond de&s;ire!</L>
<L>If hoary Time move &s;wift or &s;low,</L>
<L>I &s;eek not to inquire.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Ah! Days of bli&s;s, ye lightly pa&s;s!</L>
<L>Yet, oft, when Time would turn his hand,</L>
<L>If Lovers tears have damp'd his gla&s;s,</L>
<L>How heavy runs the &s;and!<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE></L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="37" REF="43">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE III.</HI> The Banquet Gallery, in Ruthenwolf Ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Ruthenwolf, and Claribel, &s;eated at a Banquet, under a magnificent Canopy. In the back of the Scene, above the Canopy, is a large Gothick Window. On one &s;ide, a Door, leading to another Apartment.&mdash;Va&s;&s;als and Dome&s;ticks, Male and Female, with Mu&s;ical In&s;tru|ments, in Orche&s;tras, on each &s;ide of the Gothick Window; but &s;o &s;ituated as not to have a view of the Window.&mdash;Other Va&s;&s;als, under the Orche&s;|tras.&mdash;Martin, and Rachael, in the Front of the Stage, at &s;ome di&s;tance from each other.&mdash;The Scene is &s;uperbly illuminated.</HI></STAGE>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1>
<HEAD>CHORUS.</HEAD>
<STAGE>MALE <HI>and</HI> FEMALE VASSALS.</STAGE>
<L>MELANCHOLY, hence! for merry is the fife,</L>
<L>And the lute, and the hautboy play;</L>
<L>Sorrow is a canker preying upon life;</L>
<L>To be wife is to be gay.</L>
<L><PB N="38" REF="44">Touch the chord, then, merrily, and cheerily;</L>
<L>Mu&s;ick's melody can never cloy:</L>
<L>Folly's march moves heavily and drearily,</L>
<L>Wi&s;dom's cour&s;e is joy.</L>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE><HI>During the Chorus, Martin makes &s;igns to Rachael, as anxious to &s;peak to her; as the Mu&s;ick cea&s;es, &s;he approaches him.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>Whi&s;pering.</HI></STAGE>Have you &s;een young Edmund? Did you &s;peak to him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! no; Nicholas made me quit the Lodge, while he was trying for admittance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then he is lo&s;t!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>To Martin.</HI></STAGE>What ho, there!&mdash;See to the mu&s;icians;&mdash;Our revel cools, el&s;e. Why, knave, thou &s;leep'&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who, I, my Lord?&mdash;Oh, no!&mdash;I never was merrier in all my life.&mdash;Mercy on me!&mdash; Come, boys!&mdash;"Melancholy hence! for merry is the fife.&mdash;<STAGE><HI>Singing, and offering gaiety.</HI></STAGE>&mdash; Have you appri&s;ed Lady Claribel?&mdash;<STAGE><HI>Apart to Rachael.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>Apart.</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Impo&s;&s;ible!&mdash;No moment of|fer'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Undone! &mdash; Come, fellows! &mdash; "Me|lancholy hence! &amp;c."&mdash;Strike up!&mdash;<STAGE><HI>They re|peat a &s;mall part of the Chorus.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Some wine, there!&mdash;Now, Lady! How like you the&s;e, our &s;ports?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="39" REF="45">
<SPEAKER><HI>Cla.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Sir! Wretches upon the wrack heed not the voice of revelry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, this is peevi&s;h coyne&s;s.&mdash;Come hither, fellow.&mdash;<STAGE><HI>To Martin.</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Bring thy harp.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My harp, my Lord!&mdash;Some how or other&mdash;from the damp of this gallery, I take it&mdash; my fingers tremble &s;o, I &s;hall never be able to play upon it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>Angrily.</HI></STAGE>Sing then;&mdash;your fellows &s;hall accompany you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mart.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I&mdash;I will, my lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It &s;hould &s;eem, Lady, you are not plea&s;ed with the full &s;well of min&s;trel&s;y. Haply, this fellow's &s;imple ditties may di&s;pel the cloud that hangs upon your brow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Clar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I would feign retire. 'Tis nearly, now, an hour pa&s;t midnight.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mart.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>a&s;ide.</HI></STAGE>Then he will enter the win|dow in&s;tantly!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Your patience, yet, a little, Madam. Begin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'll&mdash;Hem!&mdash;I'll give you a part of my own humble Hi&s;tory, my Lord.&mdash;And I'll put in a Chapter that may chance to &s;poil your Ban|quet.<STAGE><HI>a&s;ide.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Martin begins; accompanied by the Va&s;&s;als, in the Orche&s;tras. He appears unea&s;y during the Song
<PB N="40" REF="46">
&mdash;and looks anxiou&s;ly towards the window, at intervals.</HI></STAGE>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1>
<HEAD>ROMANCE.&mdash;MARTIN.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>NEAR the&s;e rugged Towers,</L>
<L>Where the Tempe&s;t lowers,</L>
<L>Sixteen years, in &s;orrow, I wander'd, wild.</L>
<L>Parents had left me;&mdash;</L>
<L>Death, &s;oon, of them bereft me;&mdash;</L>
<L>Woe's me! I wail'd them, an Orphan Child.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<HEAD>CHORUS.</HEAD>
<L>Ble&s;s our noble Ma&s;ter!</L>
<L>Keep him from di&s;a&s;ter!</L>
<L>Twango dillo dang&mdash;Twango dillo dee,</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Lucky was that chasing,</L>
<L>When, the Wild Boar facing,</L>
<L>Our bold Baron's life was &s;aved by me.</L>
<L>With gifts he graced me,</L>
<L>Near to his Per&s;on placed me;</L>
<L>Me a poor Pea&s;ant, of low degree.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<HEAD>CHORUS.</HEAD>
<L>Ble&s;s our noble Ma&s;ter, &amp;c.</L>
<L>All my &s;orrows over,</L>
<L>Here, I live in clover;</L>
<L>Nothing here can hurt, no Foe a&s;&s;ail.</L>
<L>This roof to enter</L>
<L>No Enemy can venture,&mdash;</L>
<L><HI>(Looking anxiou&s;ly towards the window.)</HI></L>
<L>No ra&s;h Intruder the&s;e walls can &s;cale.</L>
<L><HI>(Here the Clock tolls One.)</HI></L>
<L><HI>(Martin's trepidation increa&s;es.)</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="41" REF="47">
<HEAD>CHORUS.</HEAD>
<L>Ble&s;s our noble Ma&s;ter, &amp;c.</L>
<L>But beware to wander</L>
<L>O'er the Mountain, yonder;</L>
<L>Death is round the Lake whence this morn I came.</L>
<L><HI>(The Gothick window now opens.)</HI></L>
<L>One there did &s;natch me</L>
<L>From Fiends who would de&s;patch me;</L>
<L><HI>(Here Edmund is entering the window.)</HI></L>
<L>Edmund Fitzallan is his name.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE><HI>On hearing the name of Edmund, Claribel &s;hrieks, and falls back in her &s;eat, Ruthenwolf &s;tarts up furiou&s;ly; and Edmund leaps, unperceived, from the window, behind the Canopy.&mdash;The&s;e &s;everal movements take place at the &s;ame in&s;tant.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>ru&s;hing on Martin and holding his &s;word over him.</HI></STAGE>That hated name has cau&s;ed thy Death.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mart.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>on his knees.</HI></STAGE>Mercy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Help!&mdash;Help, the Lady Claribel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>looking round.</HI></STAGE>Ha!&mdash;fainting!&mdash;<STAGE><HI>quit|ing Martin.</HI></STAGE> Wretch! live yet a little; but &s;oon expect my vengeance.&mdash;Bear her to her cham|ber&mdash;Slaves, away! <STAGE><HI>to all the Va&s;&s;als, who go out</HI></STAGE> This way&mdash;So!&mdash;<STAGE><HI>Exit, bearing off Claribel through the door-way, on the Side.&mdash;Rachael a&s;&s;i&s;ting.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="42" REF="48"><HI>Manet</HI> MARTIN.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Edmund comes from behind the canopy, and draws upon Martin.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Villain! you have betray'd me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Don't cut my throat, it's be&s;poke by Lord Ruthenwolf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why lay this toil for me? Entice me to it, that I might peri&s;h?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What! Practice upon his life to whom I owe my own. I would peri&s;h a thou&s;and times rather than be &s;uch a &s;coundrel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How happen'd this, then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Accident. 'Twas the Baron's &s;udden hu|mour to give a fea&s;t in this Gallery, that ha&s;n't been open'd, before, the&s;e twenty years. All the means I u&s;ed to appri&s;e you of it failed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>This may be &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Kill me, el&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have been &s;een here by none but you.&mdash; We yet may pro&s;per.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There is &s;till hope.&mdash;I had, this morning, borrow'd his cloak, from our Porter, the better to conceal you.&mdash;One moment.&mdash;I have it here, at hand.<STAGE><HI>goes out.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sure I may tru&s;t this fellow.&mdash;He &s;eems earne&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="43" REF="49">
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>returning.</HI></STAGE>Here, Sir!&mdash;Now, on with it.&mdash;So&mdash;<STAGE><HI>Edmund puts on the cloak.</HI></STAGE> I'll now en|deavour to conduct you to Lady Claribel. Yon|der's her chamber.&mdash;Move &s;ilently.&mdash;Hu&s;h!<STAGE><HI>he li&s;tens at the door.</HI></STAGE> Nay, 'tis impo&s;&s;ible. The Baron's there.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ruthenwolf!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I hear him talking, at this in&s;tant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Damnation!&mdash;In her chamber!&mdash;Did worlds oppo&s;e me, this arm &s;hould drag him thence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Stay, &s;tay, &s;tay! <STAGE><HI>preventing him.</HI></STAGE> 'Tis madne&s;s.&mdash;Your de&s;truction would be certain&mdash; So would Lady Claribel's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;t I endure this!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, &s;peak lower.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, Claribel! O! torture, torture!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Edmund falls in agony, with his face upon the ground.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, we &s;hall be di&s;cover'd, and&mdash;Un|done! I hear the Baron coming!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RUTHENWOLF.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How now! Whence was that noi&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Noi&s;e, my Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye&mdash;noi&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It was&mdash;hem&mdash;&mdash;it was the Porter, my Lord. Nicholas, the Porter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="44" REF="50">
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How came he here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He&mdash;hem&mdash;hearing a kind of di&s;turbance in the Ca&s;tle, my Lord, he came to &s;ee what it was; and&mdash;being a little in his old way, my Lord&mdash;he fell upon the floor, and&mdash;and there he lyes, my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Upon the floor? This wretch, here, is the vile&s;t &s;ot&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He is a good deal di&s;gui&s;ed, ju&s;t now, indeed, my Lord. I fear he has di&s;turbed the Lady Claribel.&mdash;Any di&s;turbance he makes now, might be <HI>very dangerous to her,</HI> you know, my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Speaking with empha&s;is, that Edmund may take the hint&punc;</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No matter,&mdash;She has in&s;ulted me!&mdash; Stung me!&mdash;Fool that I was to kneel, and &s;ue, and &s;oothe, and &s;igh, and play the whining cox|comb!&mdash;By all that's galling, &s;he ca&s;t me with fury from her;&mdash;breathed execrations on the &s;avage Ruthenwolf;&mdash;then wept aloud, and call'd upon her &s;tripling, Edmund!&mdash;Oh, Lady, thou &s;halt &s;mart for this!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Was this now, my Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>not heeding him.</HI></STAGE>My cur&s;es upon Ed|mund!&mdash;Would he were here!&mdash;Would that, like this wretch, vile as the earth, whereon, a kindred clod, he grovels, Edmund were
<PB N="45" REF="51">
&s;tretch'd before me!&mdash;Thus, thus would I fix my foot upon his neck, and trample him to du&s;t</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>fixing his foot on Edmund.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I tremble in every joint!<STAGE><HI>a&s;ide.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>reflecting.</HI></STAGE>Stay!&mdash;It &s;hall be &s;o.&mdash; Come hither, &s;lave.&mdash;Thou &s;ee'&s;t this fellow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Rai&s;e him from the ground:&mdash;Then, conduct him to that apartment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To that my Lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye,&mdash;to Claribel.&mdash;Tell her I &s;corn her!&mdash;but tell her, further, that, &s;o much ten|derne&s;s is left me, I will not have her pine in maiden &s;olitude:&mdash;Therefore, &s;ince my poor love &s;eems all unworthy, I &s;end her this&mdash;ob|&s;erve me&mdash;this be&s;otted brute, who, I re&s;olve &s;hall be her hu&s;band.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You je&s;t, my Lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>By my &s;oul! ere Night once more &s;hall ca&s;t her gloomy mantle upon my battlements, their marriage, &s;hall, in the Chapel, be accom|pli&s;h'd. Take him away.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Martin rai&s;es Edmund, who hangs on Martin's &s;houlder, keeping his face concealed; and they enter Claribel's apartment.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Manet</HI> RUTHENWOLF.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, this is &s;weet revenge!&mdash;This dainty, mincing dame, who has taught her baby
<PB N="46" REF="52">
eye to &s;cowl contempt on Ruthenwolf, mu&s;t yield her poli&s;hed beauties to the meane&s;t of his va&s;&s;als.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>NICHOLAS <HI>&s;taggers in, on the oppo&s;ite &s;ide to Clari|bel's apartment.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A pretty confu&s;ion there has been in the Ca&s;tle!&mdash;I mu&s;t &s;ee if I can't put things into a little order.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Amazement!&mdash;Do I &s;ee clearly?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That depends upon how much you drank at &s;upper, my Lord. You have been making a rare racket.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>An&s;wer me, quickly. Have you not been, this very moment, in the Lady Claribel's chamber?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, fie!&mdash;I get into a lady's chamber, in the middle of the night!&mdash;But, I &s;ee how it is with you.<STAGE><HI>Pointing to his forehead.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Wretch!&mdash;Did I not &s;end thee, now, e'en now, muffled in thy cloak, into that apart|ment?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, that's a good one! How could I be in my cloak, when I lent it, this morning, to Martin?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Damnation!&mdash;Betray'd!&mdash;Nay then!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>ru&s;hes into the chamber.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="47" REF="53">
<SPEAKER><HI>Nich.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He's mon&s;trous drunk!&mdash;Well, once in a way, at a fea&s;t, it may be pardon'd.&mdash;It might have happen'd to me:&mdash;but, if he kicks up &s;uch a du&s;t, every night, I &s;hall certainly look out for a &s;oberer family.<STAGE><HI>reels out.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE IV.</HI> The Colonade, in Ruthenwolf Ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> EDMUND, CLARIBEL, MARTIN, <HI>and</HI> RA|CHAEL.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Martin conducting them.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>This way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Thus far, &s;afely. The door within thy chamber, &s;weet, that led us to the&s;e pa&s;&s;ages, was Fortune's luckie&s;t ca&s;t. Do not tremble.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Clar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Edmund! my limbs totter, and my heart &s;inks within me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, courage, Claribel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A flight of &s;teps, at the end of this build|ing, de&s;cend to the outer Court.&mdash;Cheer up, Ra|chael!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I would ri&s;k any danger with you, Mar|tin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="48" REF="54">
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The day begins to break.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So much the wor&s;e. The&s;e &s;hort Mid|&s;ummer nights are not for our bu&s;ine&s;s. Secre|cy is a mole, and loves to work in the dark. This way, Lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Clar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hark!&mdash;Heard you not the trampling of feet?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mart.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No;&mdash;all's &s;ecure. The Baron is hug|ging him&s;elf, in his fancied revenge. We &s;hall e&s;cape from the clutches of as errant a ty|rant as ever&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>without.</HI></STAGE>Secure the Gates! Guard every avenue.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> RUTHENWOLF.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>running to Martin, whom he fir&s;t &s;ees.</HI></STAGE>Now meet thy puni&s;hment.&mdash;But hold&mdash;On one condition I may &s;pare thee.&mdash;Confe&s;s who 'tis for whom thou ha&s;t, thus, plotted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>One who &s;aved the life you are going to take. So take it while I can part with it coolly&mdash;for I &s;hould be afraid to die could I be treacherous to my pre&s;erver.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The torture, then, &s;hall wring his name from thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>coming forward, and di&s;covering him&s;elf.</HI></STAGE>'Tis a name &s;oon utter'd.&mdash;Edmund Fitzallan.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="49" REF="55">
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, blu&s;h at it.&mdash;I am in your toil. You are now mo&s;t powerful:&mdash;but, how meanly, even to him&s;elf, appears the man who feels that he has power, and feels, he has abu&s;ed it!&mdash;How little looks the ba&s;e Oppre&s;&s;or, when the &s;ufferer from his oppre&s;&s;ion &s;tands before him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>In Warfare, boy, Policy has its privi|lege. You have experienced my &s;kill in &s;trata|gem; acknowledge, now, my force.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It mu&s;t be, then, in death.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>They fight&mdash;and, as they are engaged, a loud &s;hout is heard, and the di&s;charge of Cannon.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Several Va&s;&s;als.&mdash;They &s;urround Edmund.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1<HI>&s;t. Va&s;&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To Arms, my Lord!&mdash;The Ca&s;tle is &s;uddenly attack'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Say you?&mdash;By whom?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Va&s;&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A powerful Troop, my Lord, pouring down the Mountain, from the wood; headed by Baron Fitzallan, and his &s;ons&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Cur&s;e on the name!&mdash;Mu&s;ter the men. &mdash;I come.&mdash;Conduct the&s;e to the Black Tower, that overhangs the We&s;tern Battlement.&mdash;Guard them &s;ecurely. After the battle, Stripling, I &s;hall di&s;po&s;e thy fate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Edm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Till then, tremble for thy own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Clar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, Ruthenwolf&mdash;Tremble; while we are tranquil. Marking the &s;teps of Time, Vice
<PB N="50" REF="56">
&s;hudders at the future, and meets Adve$&s;ity with agony;&mdash;but Virtue can, calmly, gaze on Fortune, as &s;he turns her wheel;&mdash;can look for|ward to her &s;miles, with cheerfulne&s;s, or endure her frown, with &s;teady re&s;ignation.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt</HI> EDMUND <HI>and</HI> CLARIBEL, <HI>guarded.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Shouts, and Cannonading, repeated.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They thunder at our walls.&mdash;Sound the alarum!&mdash;Well, let him come:&mdash;&s;urrounded with his &s;ons,&mdash;the better;&mdash;that with one blow I may de&s;troy both Stock and Cion, and exterminate the hated growth for ever.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.&mdash;Va&s;&s;als following.&mdash;A Flouri&s;h.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Manent</HI> MARTIN <HI>and</HI> RACHAEL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So!&mdash;In the bu&s;tle he has forgot me. What a &s;nug covering is in&s;ignificance!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Martin! what will become of us!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Chance mu&s;t decide, Rachael.&mdash;I wi&s;h, now there is danger,&mdash;I had not brought you to the Ca&s;tle!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>mournfully</HI></STAGE>Do you indeed, Martin?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That I do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am very &s;orry you &s;hould think me hollow-hearted!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mart.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I think!&mdash;How, Rachael?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rach.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e, Martin, one of the greate&s;t pains a poor girl's heart can feel is, &s;urely, being
<PB N="51" REF="57">
ab&s;ent from him &s;he loves, when &s;he knows he is in affliction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mar.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>embracing her</HI></STAGE>My dear Rachael!</P>
<STAGE><HI>Shouts and Trumpets.</HI></STAGE>
<P>Hark&mdash;I have little time for thought.&mdash;There is a pa&s;&s;age, under the Ca&s;tle, to the moat.&mdash;There I may be of &s;ervice&mdash;You mu&s;t thither with me.&mdash; I care not on my own account;&mdash;tis for you, the Lady Claribel, and my Pre&s;erver, that I am anxious.&mdash;Something tells me, &s;till, I &s;hall pro&s;per in my endeavours&mdash;for 'tis hard fate if a man fail when Love, Pity, and Gratitude, are the &s;prings of his action.<STAGE><HI>Exeunt</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Shouts, and Alarums repeated.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE THE LAST.</HI> On the right of the Stage, is the exterior of Ruthen|wolf Ca&s;tle. The Chief Entrance is repre&s;ented in a &s;ide view; con&s;isting of a Gateway, between two Turrets;&mdash;the Bridge drawn up. The Ca&s;t|le is partially moated;&mdash;the water lo&s;ing it&s;elf un|der a low arch, beneath the battlements, before it has completely encircled the building:&mdash;But the
<PB N="52" REF="58">
Battlements are continued beyond the place where the moat is lo&s;t; and at the ba&s;e of the&s;e is a Sally Port, clo&s;e to the ground. Above them, a black round Tower.<LB>From a window in the round Tower, and, al&s;o, from a window in one $word$ the turrets, are flights of &s;teps, which communicate with the ramparts.<LB>On the left of the Stage, are high tufted Trees: At the back, Mountains, in per&s;pective, and the Sun ri&s;ing above them.<LB>Fitzallan, Henry, and Orlando are drawn up on the left, with Soldiery and Cannon, &amp;c. &amp;c. Pio|neers at work upon a Mine, at the mouth of the Sally Port; beneath the Round Tower. The moment the Scene is di&s;clo&s;ed, a loud Shout, and a heavy can|nonade, from Fitzallan's party;&mdash;with a &s;hower of Arrows&mdash;which is return'd by Ruthenwolf's Soldiery, who are thickly placed on the Turrets.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>After this bur&s;t, a Parley is &s;ounded from the wall.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hark! They &s;ound a Parley.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>RUTHENWOLF <HI>appears on the Walls.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Henry.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>By all our wrongs! 'tis Ruthenwolf!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye;&mdash;to hurl de&s;truction on thee; e'en like the angry Lion, bru&s;hing the in&s;ects from his lip, who fret him in his &s;lumbers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Vain man! our &s;ting, we tru&s;t, will be found &s;harp, provoked, thus, as we are, by bitter
<PB N="53" REF="59">
injury.&mdash;Yet, now, re&s;tore thy Captive, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Never!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Henry.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Renew the attack!<STAGE><HI>Archers prepare.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hold! you run upon your ruin. My numbers here, Fitzallan, exceed thine, trebly:&mdash; And &s;till, more &s;urely to baffle this your ill-advi&s;ed attempt, behind your wretched troop my parties march; and, by my order, winding along the vale, will pre&s;s upon you. You are &s;urrounded.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Here Ruthenwolf's men appear, in per&s;pective, marching to &s;urround Fitzallan.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, then, the ca&s;t is de&s;perate.&mdash;Apply your Torches to the train, and &s;pring the Mine. <STAGE><HI>The Pioneers &s;et fire to a train of Powder.</HI></STAGE> Thus we will gain entrance; and, though we peri&s;h, we will, in peri&s;hing, revenge our Hou&s;e's wrongs.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! Ha! Ha!&mdash;'Tis rarely plan'd.&mdash; Yon Tower may well be &s;pared;&mdash;a rude excre&s;|cence in this fair Pile.&mdash;But, 'thad been well, ere you applied the Torch, to think the Tower might, po&s;&s;ibly, contain, among&s;t the ru&s;t which lyes neglected there, your Son and Claribel.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>EDMUND and CLARIBEL <HI>appear at the window of the Tower.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Heaven! My Son!&mdash;Quick!&mdash; quench your fires.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="54" REF="60">
<SPEAKER><HI>Ruth.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay 'tis impo&s;&s;ible. Your men, no doubt, are dext'rous. The train &s;eems too well laid. We trifle time. Down with the Draw-bridge! We'll forth, and end this conte&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>He de&s;cends from the Battlements, as going to the Draw-bridge.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Hen.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Charge &s;till!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Charge.&mdash;During this conflict, Edmund wrenches a bar from the window of the Tower, in which he and Claribel are confined.&mdash;As the Draw-bridge is let down, Martin, with Rachael, appear in a Boat, from the low arch.&mdash;Martin paddles to the Draw-bridge, and &s;aws the joi&s;ts.&mdash;The moment Ruthenwolf ru&s;hes upon it, to lead on his men, it breaks under him.&mdash;He is plunged into the Moat, and the waters cover him.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>A LOUD HUZZA. <HI>Martin jumps to land, conduct|ing Rachael, on the &s;ide of the Fitzallans.&mdash;At this moment, Edmund has made an aperture in the window, and leads Claribel ha&s;tily down the flight of &s;teps, to the ramparts.&mdash;The Mine &s;prings, and blows up the Round Tower.&mdash;They now a&s;cend the other &s;tair, belonging to the win|dow of the turret.&mdash;They enter that window, and then appear at the broken Draw-bridge.&mdash;Mar|tin's Boat, lying acro&s;s the water, &s;erves them to pa&s;s to the Fitzallan party.&mdash;While they are cro&s;&s;ing, the turret, al&s;o, which they had ju&s;t en|tered,
<PB N="55" REF="61">
blows up, and di&s;covers the Stair-ca&s;e they have de&s;cended, to e&s;cape from the Ca&s;tle.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>SHOUTS AND ACCLAMATIONS</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>The Flags of the remaining part of the Ca&s;tle are &s;truck.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fitz.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>embracing Edmund and Claribel.</HI></STAGE>Oh, this is triumph!&mdash;Thoughts ru&s;h in wild confu|&s;ion now; and feelings are too high for utter|ance.&mdash;When pa&s;&s;ions cool, we will reward our friends, and&mdash;I can no more!&mdash;My old heart pants with tran&s;port; and my broken accents can merely pay a feeble, but a grateful tribute, to that Power which &s;hields the Virtuous,</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1>
<HEAD>GRAND CHORUS.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SOLDIERS, VASSALS, &amp;c.</STAGE>
<L>NOW be the Clarion &s;hrilly &s;ounded!</L>
<L>Loud the bla&s;t of Triumph breathe!</L>
<L>Guilt and Rapine &s;ink confounded;</L>
<L>Virtue wears the laurel'd wreathe.</L>
<L>'Tis &s;weet when Conque&s;t ends the &s;trife;</L>
<L>While, with the drum, and merry &s;ounding fife,</L>
<L>The jolly &s;oldiers march along the plain,</L>
<L>To greet their wives, their children, and their friends again.</L>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<TRAILER>THE END.</TRAILER>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT>
